<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Heavyweight Riddick Bowe remained undefeated, stopping former World Boxing 
Council champion Pinklon Thomas on an eighth-round technical knockout at 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
It was the 17th knockout for Bowe (19-0), who battered Thomas through most of 
the scheduled 10-rounder until the 32-year-old fighter could not answer the 
bell for the ninth round. 
</P>
<P>
The victory is expected to earn Bowe a bout against Bert Cooper on the 
undercard of the Buster Douglas-Evander Holyfield title fight Oct. 25. 
</P>
<P>
"It was a learning experience and Pinklon brought the best out in me," Bowe 
said. "Some say he's washed up, a has-been. But he brought out the best in me. 
I don't care what any of you guys say." 
</P>
<P>
In the sixth round, Thomas was staggered but wouldn't fall as Bowe weakened him 
with a series of quick combinations. Bowe swung freely for Thomas' head in the 
last three rounds as many in the crowd shouted for referee Sylvester Stevens to 
stop the fight. 
</P>
<P>
Thomas shook his head at Stevens after stumbling back to his corner after the 
eighth, finally ending the fight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
