<HEADLINE>
<P>
PARLIAMENT BACKS THATCHER ON GULF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Britain's Parliament on Friday strongly backed Prime Minister Margaret 
Thatcher's dispatch of forces to the Persian Gulf and her refusal to rule out 
military action against Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
At the end of a two-day emergency debate, the House of Commons supported 
government policy by a vote of 437 to 35, far higher than the 100-seat majority 
Thatcher's Conservatives normally command in the 650-member chamber. 
</P>
<P>
Britain was the first country to commit forces to back the U.S. military 
buildup in the gulf after Iraq's Aug. 2 seizure of Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
Britain has sent three squadrons of fighter-bomber aircraft, a destroyer and 
two frigates to the area. A second destroyer and three minesweepers are also on 
their way. Officials said a further commitment would almost certainly be ground 
troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
