<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEEKEND TV; 
</P>
<P>
SUMMIT, FOOTBALL, NEW SHOWS TOO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE WEINSTEIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
News of the Bush-Gorbachev summit in Finland and the tense situation in the 
Persian Gulf is likely to overshadow everything else this weekend -- even the 
kickoff of the pro football season, the finals of the U.S. Open tennis 
tournament and the debuts of several new entertainment shows. 
</P>
<P>
Prior to the season premiere of "NFL Live" Sunday, for example, NBC will 
broadcast 4 1/2 hours of live news from the summit, beginning at 5 a.m. ABC, 
CBS and CNN will also provide extensive coverage of the meetings in Helsinki 
all weekend. 
</P>
<P>
NBC (4)(36)(39) debuts "The Fanelli Boys," a new sitcom about an Italian 
family, tonight at 9:30 p.m. (The show will air regularly this season on 
Wednesdays at 9 p.m.) Following at 10 p.m., Gary Collins hosts the "Miss 
America Pageant." 
</P>
<P>
Fox counters at 10 p.m. tonight with the Mardi Gras premiere of Mark Frost's 
and David Lynch's new documentary series, "American Chronicles." 
</P>
<P>
Sunday, "The Late Mr. Pete Show," once an outrageous Westside public access 
cable talk show, moves to broadcast television on Channel 5 at 11:30 p.m. Mr. 
Pete (Peter Chaconas), the flamboyant host who habitually sports a hideous 
plaid red jacket, is nothing if he is not one zany guy. Martin Mull guests. 
STEVE WEINSTEIN 
</P>
</TEXT>
